				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Avoiding a Climate Inferno</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Andrew C. Revkin			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-07-07T16:07:29+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 7, 2015 12:07 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 7, 2015 12:07 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/07/avoiding-a-climate-inferno/" data-title="Avoiding a Climate Inferno" data-description="The editor of the journal Science says it is time to get serious about cutting greenhouse gas emissions. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The current issueÂ of Science features <a href="//www.sciencemag.org/content/349/6243/7.full">a short, but forceful editorial</a>Â by the journal&#8217;s editor in chief, the geophysicist <a href="//www.aaas.org/news/marcia-mcnutt-named-new-editor-chief-science">Marcia K. McNutt</a>, calling for humanity, after decades of delay, to get serious about cutting greenhouse-gas emissions linked to global warming.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;The time for debate has ended,&#8221; she writes. &#8220;Action is urgently needed.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">McNutt (who was just <a href="//www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=07062015">nominated* to be the next president of the National Academy of Sciences</a>)Â points to studies showing that nations&#8217; emissions-cutting pledges made ahead of <a href="//www.cop21.gouv.fr/en">Paris climate treaty talks</a> this December are insufficient to keep the planet from heating up beyond the 2-degree Celsius threshold the world&#8217;sÂ nations previously agreed to avoid. (Learn more about that seemingly simple, but very complicated, temperature targetÂ <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/09/the-two-degree-solution/">here</a> and <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/03/getting-over-the-2-degree-limit-on-global-warming/">here</a>.)</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/06/blogs/dotdanteinferno/dotdanteinferno-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/06/blogs/dotdanteinferno/dotdanteinferno-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/06/blogs/dotdanteinferno/dotdanteinferno-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003784033" width="190" height="149" alt="One ofÂ Gustave DorÃ©&#039;s illustrations from aÂ &lt;a href=&quot;//www.gutenberg.org/files/8789/8789-h/8789-h.htm&quot;&gt;19th century edition&lt;/a&gt;Â of Dante&#039;s &quot;Inferno.&quot;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="149"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">One ofÂ Gustave DorÃ©'s illustrations from aÂ <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/files/8789/8789-h/8789-h.htm">19th century edition</a>Â of Dante's "Inferno."</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Gustave DorÃ©</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">McNutt frames her argument around moralityÂ as much as data, alluding to <a href="//j.mp/danteinfernodore">Dante&#8217;s 14th-century allegorical journey</a> through hell inÂ setting the tone of her piece:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Dante&#8217;s Inferno, he describes the nine circles of Hell, each dedicated to different sorts of sinners, with the outermost being occupied by those who didn&#8217;t know any better, and the innermost reserved for the most treacherous offenders. I wonder where in the nine circles Dante would place all of us who are borrowing against this Earth in the name of economic growth, accumulating an environmental debt by burning fossil fuels, the consequences of which will be left for our children and grandchildren to bear?</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In that vein, she also credits Pope Francis for pressing for action. (McNutt delivered <a href="//www.pas.va/content/dam/accademia/pdf/es41/es41-mcnutt.pdf">a paper on coastal risk</a> at the 2014 Vatican meeting that <a href="//j.mp/dotvatican">laid the foundation</a> for much of the papal encyclical on the environment and humanity; <a href="//j.mp/dotpope">my views on Francis&#8217;s involvement are here</a>.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The editorial is passionate and pointed but &#8212; perhaps due toÂ compression &#8212; has a passage that is likely to irk India and misses an important opportunity by not mentioning theÂ vital need for greatly boosted public investments in basic energy-related research as a critical facetÂ of any plausible deep decarbonization push.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read on for a couple of excerpts and my comments. Here&#8217;s the problematic passage on India: <span id="more-55381"></span></p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unfortunately, Piyush Goyal, India&#8217;s Minister of State for Power, Coal, and New and Renewable Energy, intends to double his nation&#8217;s coal production by the year 2019 to meet domestic energy requirements. China appears to be taking the opposite track, recognizing its vulnerability to climate change and investing heavily in renewable energy. [<em>Her r<a href="//www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-33040965">eference is here</a></em>.]Â Like California, China is betting that good environmental policy will make for good fiscal policy by being in the vanguard of the clean energy economy.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The problem?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">India has justifiably resisted efforts to equate its obligations with those of China. Just look at per capita carbon dioxide emissions to understand why. Indiaâs annual emissions per person stood <a href="//www.zmescience.com/ecology/world-problems/china-eu-co2-emissions-22092014/">at 1.9 tons</a> in the latest analysis. China, with its coal-fired push to cut poverty, is now atÂ <a href="//www.zmescience.com/ecology/world-problems/china-eu-co2-emissions-22092014/">7.2 tons</a> per person per year. (Europe is at 6.8 tons and the United States 16.4 tons.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Indiaâs <a href="//www.technologyreview.com/news/535551/indias-ambitious-bid-to-become-a-solar-power/">ambitious pledge to expandÂ generation from solar</a>, wind and other renewable energy sources is great, but will long remain frosting on a fossil fuel cake. Its demand for a substantial portion of the atmosphereâs remaining â<a href="//www.ibtimes.co.uk/un-climate-talks-india-seeks-equitable-carbon-space-lima-event-notches-record-carbon-footprint-1478876">carbon space</a>â &#8212; essentially making room for that coal growth &#8212; is legitimate and ethical, as long as it is doing whatever it can (with financing or technical help from rich countries) to build the <a href="//cornerstonemag.net/upgrading-the-efficiency-of-the-worlds-coal-fleet-to-reduce-co2-emissions/">most efficient, cleanest coal plants possible</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even Mark Lynas, the British climate campaigner and author of &#8220;<a href="//www.amazon.com/Six-Degrees-Future-Hotter-Planet/dp/1426203853">Six Degrees: Our Future on a Hotter Planet</a>,&#8221; hasÂ <a href="//www.marklynas.org/2014/11/indias-coal-conundrum-which-comes-first-the-climate-or-the-poor/">acknowledged India&#8217;s right to burn more coal</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Listen to my <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8T8O1vXpci0">recent chat with Jairam Ramesh</a>, India&#8217;s former environment minister and author of &#8220;<a href="//www.hindustantimes.com/books/book-review-jairam-ramesh-s-green-signals-shows-growth-s-not-just-gdp/article1-1328999.aspx">Green Signals</a>,&#8221; for more on what India can do with renewable energy and must do with coal. India has <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/31/the-power-gap-behind-indias-mass-blackouts/">several hundred million citizens</a> without access to more than a dribble of electricity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Research Gap</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was also discouraged that the piece didn&#8217;t expressly callÂ for a big boost inÂ public fundingÂ for basic energy-related science, particularly given the <a href="//www.aaas.org/page/historical-trends-federal-rd">longtime focus</a> of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the journal&#8217;s publisher, on <a href="//www.aaas.org/news/aaas-analysis-shows-uncertain-future-federal-rd-spending">declining government investments in basicÂ research</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Click back to my 2006 article, &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2006/10/30/business/worldbusiness/30energy.html?scp=1&amp;sq=Budgets+Falling+in+Race+to+Fight+Global+Warming&amp;st=nyt">Budgets Falling in Race to Fight Global Warming,</a>&#8221; to see data on energy research at that timeÂ from the invaluable A.A.A.S. R&amp;D Budget and Policy Program. Things are no better now, and the underinvestment in energy research is a consistent pattern across theÂ world&#8217;s wealthy countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For more, read my 2014 article on how the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/panels-latest-warming-warning-misses-global-slumber-party-on-energy-research/">left out this energy research gap</a> in its 2014 synthesis report. It&#8217;s worth reposting two graphsÂ showing that we invest in science on issues we care about &#8212; national defense and health, mostly &#8212; and hardly invest at all in advancing knowledge on energy frontiers despite so many statements, including McNutt&#8217;s, saying this is the prime challenge of our age.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here&#8217;s the United States research portfolio since Sputnik:<br />
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotipccrdd/dotipccrdd-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotipccrdd/dotipccrdd-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotipccrdd/dotipccrdd-blog480.jpg" id="100000003211085" width="480" height="362" alt="In the United States, &lt;a href=&quot;//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/?s=koizumi+research+development+defense&quot;&gt;federal investments in energy research&lt;/a&gt; have never come close to those in areas that are high priorities. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.aaas.org/sites/default/files/Function_0.jpg&quot;&gt;Military research is greater&lt;/a&gt; than that in all these areas combined."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="362"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">In the United States, <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/?s=koizumi+research+development+defense">federal investments in energy research</a> have never come close to those in areas that are high priorities. <a href="//www.aaas.org/sites/default/files/Function_0.jpg">Military research is greater</a> than that in all these areas combined.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> OSTP.gov</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here&#8217;s the pattern across the members of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, or O.E.C.D.:</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotIEArd/dotIEArd-blog480.png" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotIEArd/dotIEArd-blog480.png" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/02/blogs/dotIEArd/dotIEArd-blog480.png" id="100000003211092" width="480" height="152" alt="Expanded access to clean energy is an underpinning of global wellbeing, but energy research &lt;a href=&quot;//www.iea.org/etp/tracking/figures/rdd_innovation/&quot;&gt;remains a low priority for the world&#039;s wealthy democracies&lt;/a&gt;. This graph shows O.E.C.D. countriesâ spending on research, development and demonstration as a share of total research budgets"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="152"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Expanded access to clean energy is an underpinning of global wellbeing, but energy research <a href="//www.iea.org/etp/tracking/figures/rdd_innovation/">remains a low priority for the world's wealthy democracies</a>. This graph shows O.E.C.D. countriesâ spending on research, development and demonstration as a share of total research budgets</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> International Energy Agency (OECD data)</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Basic researchÂ is the no-quick-payoff grunt work that entrepreneurs and venture investors build revolutions on.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In considering the need for a boost, don&#8217;t take my word for it. A new paper in Climate Policy, &#8220;<a href="//www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14693062.2015.1037820#preview">Energy research within the UNFCCC: A proposal to guard against ongoing climate-deadlock</a>,&#8221; cites the need and proposes that research commitments be included in national pledges under the climate treaty. (UNFCCC is the acronym for the 1992 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, the basic treaty that all subsequent climate diplomacy, including whatever happens in Paris in December, is built on.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here&#8217;s the authors&#8217; logic:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The higher costs associated with low-emissions alternatives to fossil fuels currently creates [<em>sic</em>] significant economic and political resistance to their widespread adoption. To breach this impasse, a mechanism supporting accelerated energy research is needed that seeks to reduce future abatement costs, share experience and âlearning-by-doingâ in first-of-a-kind demonstrations, and thus facilitate future widespread deployments. These actions will also assist in addressing inequalities in energy access.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This paper reminded me of a question I posed to Bush administration climate negotiators in 2008: would the world have been better off signing a <a href="//blogs.cfr.org/levi/2010/12/10/should-the-climate-talks-be-focused-on-technology/">Framework Convention on Technology Change</a> back in 1992 instead of one on climate change? (<a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/climate-and-energy-beyond-cancun/">Click here for their answer and mine</a>.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another valuable reference to the need for a big research boost came in last year&#8217;s &#8220;<a href="//unsdsn.org/what-we-do/deep-decarbonization-pathways/">Pathways to Deep Decarbonization</a>&#8221; report from the <a href="//unsdsn.org/">Sustainable Development Solutions Network</a>, an initiative spearheaded by Columbia University economist Jeff Sachs. Here&#8217;s the key line:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;[C]ountries and the international community as a whole must undertake a major research, development, demonstration, and diffusion (RDD&amp;D) effort to develop low-carbon technologies and ensure their widespread availability and their cost-competitiveness with high-carbon alternatives&#8230;&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The roots of this line of thinking go back at least to 1998 and an important paper by Marty Hoffert, Ken Caldeira and others titled &#8220;<a href="//www.nature.com/nature/journal/v395/n6705/abs/395881a0.html">Energy implications of future stabilization of atmospheric CO2 content.</a>&#8221; Here&#8217;s the key conclusion:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The magnitude of the implied infrastructure transition suggests the need for massive investments in innovative energy research.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;d be great if McNutt would consider following up on her call for emissionsÂ action with a deeper dive on the role of science in facilitating such action. And of course her next home, the National Academy of Sciences, can keep building on the valuable work it has done on this question.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#8217;ve just arrived at <a href="//www.commonfuture-paris2015.org/The-Conference/Why-this-conference.htm">Our Common Future Under Climate Change</a>, a conference in Paris, organized by the French government and others, at which this theme has already come up. I&#8217;ll be filing on the meeting through Friday. You can track Twitter output via the <a href="//twubs.com/cfcc15">#CFCC15</a> hashtag.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Addendum</em>:Â On Sunday, the climate scientist Judith Curry <a href="//judithcurry.com/2015/07/05/the-beyond-two-degree-inferno/">was sharply critical of McNutt&#8217;s editorial,</a> particularly on the assertion that &#8220;the time for debate has ended.&#8221; Curry, as you know, has focused her blog and public commentary for years on the remaining scientific questions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I agree with her that there is plenty to debate, both on the science in tough areas like attribution and climate sensitivity and on what mix ofÂ incentives, investments, policies, communication efforts and other actions can build a more durable human relationship with the climate system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But I agree with McNutt (and Pope Francis and many others) that the need to pursue <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/?s=%22for+the+long+haul%22+energy">an energy menu that works for the long haul</a>Â is well established.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I don&#8217;t agree with Curry&#8217;s concerns that the editorial could influence how the journal assesses research papers submitted for publication. A wide array of science journals, from Science and Nature to the New England Journal of Medicine, have a long history of taking strong editorial positions while maintaining (as much as possible) the integrity of the peer review and publishing process. They have firewalls just like the one at The Times separating Opinion and News.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I checked in with the press office at A.A.A.S. to be sure I was up to date on relevant policies. Here&#8217;s what I was sent:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our official language concerning the opinion pieces published byÂ ScienceÂ appears at the bottom of <a href="//www.sciencemag.org/content/349/6243/local/masthead.pdf">our masthead</a>. The relevant excerpt reads as follows:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âScienceÂ serves as a forum for discussion of important issues related to the advancement of science by publishing material on which a consensus has been reached as well as including the presentation of minority of conflicting points of view. Accordingly, all articles published inÂ Scienceâincluding editorials, news and comment, and books reviewsâare signed and reflect the individual views of the authors and not official points of view adopted byÂ AAASÂ or the institutions with which the authors are affiliated.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All editorials published inÂ ScienceÂ reflect the views of the signing author(s). We strive to provide transparency by ensuring that each editorial has a signature, as that is an important piece of information for the reader.</p></blockquote>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: July 7, 2015</strong> <br>* I initially wrote that Marcia McNutt was elected to lead the National Academy of Sciences. She was nominated. The election late this year is a formality (she's the only nominee).</div></div>	</div>
